        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the brownie base",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Preheat the oven to 175°C conventional (155°C fan). Grease and line a 20 × 20 cm square tin with baking paper. Melt the dark chocolate and butter together in a heatproof bowl set over a pan of barely simmering water, stirring occasionally. Remove from the heat and cool for 5 minutes. Whisk in the sugar, then the eggs one at a time. Fold in the flour, cocoa, and salt until just combined. Pour three-quarters of the brownie batter into the prepared tin.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the cream cheese layer",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Beat the cream cheese and sugar together until smooth, then beat in the egg and vanilla. The mixture should be pourable but not runny. Spread it over the brownie batter in the tin, then spoon the remaining brownie batter over the top in dollops.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Swirl and bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Draw a skewer or knife through the surface five or six times in a figure-of-eight pattern to create the swirl. Bake for 30 to 35 minutes until the edges are clearly set, the centre has a slight wobble, and a skewer through the brownie section (avoiding the cream cheese) comes out with moist crumbs attached, not raw batter. Cool in the tin for 1 hour, then refrigerate for at least 1 hour before cutting; the brownie needs to be cold and firm for clean slices.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
